replies.commentText:
@Matthew P.
I disagree that it was a "decent debate" and found it to be mostly vacuous and uninformative.
Your articulated comments here, however, are excellent and really should have been presented live as the on-air material for this CBC segment instead.

@Confucius This particular discussion is a rarity, though. At present I'm checking out Peter Mansbridge's last "At Issue' to which the commenting is closed. This fact alone should NEVER occur nor be censored where they have (they remove comments to shape the impression of respondants!) 

The fact that on that "At Issue" asks what was most assumed to be significant as a change, two factors stand out: technology AND an almost universal imbalance of women on staff. The commenting that gets censored is to 'protect' those presumed 'weak' without realizing such behavior WEAKENS democratic freedoms of the people. It appears that the means to defeat discrimination has the tendency to merely TRANSFER which groups are favored rather than become more universal against it.

We NEED more power to speak than is being offered, especially on the CBC sites directly. They are censored in discretion with absolute protection to hide WHO the censors are. But I once pointed out that our 'Canadian' sites are not even OURS. The censoring is thus of some private interest group who owns the sites and could represent ANYONE, even a foreign interest group. They are clearly ANTI-freedom of speech components who are 'sensitive' to jump on 'hate' accusations uncertainly founded (because we can no longer see them to judge.)
